\begin_layout Section
The BOI Monetary Policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the monetary decision process, the economy is analyzed first, then inflation
 and finally the exchange rate.
 In normal times, only interest rate and FX intervention take place, but
 during a crisis QE can be applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strength of the Israeli economy lies in its stable banks and financial
 markets (which was not the case before 2002, when the ratio of the debt
 to GDP was around 95%).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at the 10 year rates in Israel during 2007-2021, we can see that
 they are 
\series bold
lower
\series default
 the in the U.S, and the historical lowest ever - means that the markets
 provide extremely low probability for the default of Israel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Israel has become more closed during the last 15 years (the exports and
 imports going from ~40% to ~25% of GDP).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exchange rate gets stronger, which reduces prices.
 Given the ZLB, the BOI tries to prevent that by intervening more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2013 gas was discovered in Israel and the high-tech sector boomed, therefore
 the interest rate decreased dramatically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are the reasons for the low Inflation in Israel? By decomposing the
 inflation to tradable vs.
 non-tradable goods index, we can see that the main reason is appreciation
 of the Shekel.
\end_layout

